          "type": "plan",
          "text": "# How git-ai Selects Files to Track During Checkpointing\n\n## Overview\n\ngit-ai's checkpoint system tracks files at character/line granularity to attribute code changes to humans or AI agents. The file selection process determines *which files* get included in each checkpoint. This document traces the complete logic flow, from entry point to final file list, with code pointers to every important decision.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Entry Points\n\nThere are three ways a checkpoint can be initiated:\n\n### 1a. Synchronous checkpoint: `run()`\n**File:** `src/commands/checkpoint.rs:309`\n\nCalled directly by the CLI (`git-ai checkpoint <agent> [files...]`) or by hooks. Delegates to `run_with_base_commit_override()` (line 331), which delegates to `run_with_base_commit_override_with_policy()` (line 355).\n\n### 1b. Prepared (async) checkpoint: `prepare_captured_checkpoint()`\n**File:** `src/commands/checkpoint.rs:838`\n\nUsed for deferred/async checkpoints. Captures a snapshot of file states at invocation time, stores them to `~/.git-ai/internal/async-checkpoint-blobs/{capture_id}/`, then later replayed via `execute_captured_checkpoint()` (line 984). **Requires** explicit `edited_filepaths` or `will_edit_filepaths` from the agent.\n\n### 1c. Post-commit hook\n**File:** `src/authorship/post_commit.rs`\n\nRuns after `git commit`. Converts working logs into `AuthorshipLog` and stores as a Git note at `refs/notes/ai`. Does not select files itself — it processes whatever checkpoints already exist.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The Core Resolution Pipeline\n\nAll synchronous checkpoints flow through this chain:\n\n```\nrun() \n  -> run_with_base_commit_override()           [line 331]\n    -> run_with_base_commit_override_with_policy()  [line 355]\n      -> resolve_live_checkpoint_execution()    [line 489]  <-- FILE SELECTION HAPPENS HERE\n      -> execute_resolved_checkpoint()          [line 625]  <-- PROCESSES THE SELECTED FILES\n```\n\n### 2a. `resolve_live_checkpoint_execution()` — the orchestrator\n**File:** `src/commands/checkpoint.rs:489-622`\n\nThis function is the single decision point that determines which files end up in the checkpoint. It returns a `ResolvedCheckpointExecution` containing a `files: Vec<String>` and `dirty_files: HashMap<String, String>`.\n\n**Step-by-step flow:**\n\n1. **Resolve base commit** (line 497): Uses `resolve_base_commit()` (line 206) — takes the override if provided, otherwise reads `HEAD`. Falls back to `\"initial\"` if no HEAD exists (empty repo).\n\n2. **Reject bare repos** (line 499): Checkpoints cannot run on bare repositories.\n\n3. **Build ignore patterns** (line 508): Calls `effective_ignore_patterns(repo, &[], &[])` to assemble the full ignore list (see Section 4).\n\n4. **Load working log** (line 513): Opens `PersistedWorkingLog` for the base commit from `.git/ai/working_logs/{base_commit_sha}/`.\n\n5. **Inject dirty files** (line 523): If the agent provided `dirty_files` in its `AgentRunResult`, these are injected into the working log via `set_dirty_files()`.\n\n6. **Filter agent pathspecs** (line 533): Calls `filtered_pathspecs_for_agent_run_result()` (line 397) to get explicit file paths from the agent, validated against the repo boundary.\n\n7. **Base-override fast path** (line 542-587): If a `base_commit_override` is provided AND explicit paths + dirty files are available, it uses `resolve_base_override_dirty_file_execution()` (line 442) to bypass the expensive git status scan entirely. This is the daemon commit replay optimization for macOS.\n\n8. **Main file collection** (line 590): Calls `get_all_tracked_files()` — **the core file selection function** (see Section 3).\n\n9. **Attach dirty file contents** (line 605-614): Maps dirty file content to the resolved file list.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `get_all_tracked_files()` — The Core File Selection Logic\n\n**File:** `src/commands/checkpoint.rs:1105-1262`\n\nThis is the most important function for understanding file tracking. It assembles the complete file list from **five sources**, applies filtering at each step, then merges them via a git status call.\n\n### Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Purpose |\n|-----------|---------|\n| `repo` | Git repository handle |\n| `_base_commit` | (unused) Base commit SHA |\n| `working_log` | Persisted working log with checkpoint history |\n| `edited_filepaths` | Explicit paths from agent (already filtered by `filtered_pathspecs_for_agent_run_result`) |\n| `is_pre_commit` | Whether this is a pre-commit (human) checkpoint |\n| `preserve_explicit_pre_commit_paths` | Whether to force-include agent-provided paths even if git status doesn't report them |\n| `ignore_matcher` | Compiled ignore pattern matcher |\n\n### Source 1: Explicit paths from agent (line 1114-1123)\n\n```rust\nlet explicit_pre_commit_paths: HashSet<String> = edited_filepaths\n    .map(|paths| paths.iter()\n        .map(|path| normalize_to_posix(path))\n        .filter(|path| !should_ignore_file_with_matcher(path, ignore_matcher))\n        .collect())\n    .unwrap_or_default();\nlet mut files = explicit_pre_commit_paths.clone();\n```\n\nThese come from `AgentRunResult.edited_filepaths` (for AI checkpoints) or `AgentRunResult.will_edit_filepaths` (for human/pre-commit checkpoints). They are the files the agent explicitly reported touching. The selection logic is in `explicit_capture_target_paths()` (line 178):\n\n- **Human checkpoint (`CheckpointKind::Human`):** Uses `will_edit_filepaths` with role `PreparedPathRole::WillEdit`\n- **AI checkpoint:** Uses `edited_filepaths` with role `PreparedPathRole::Edited`\n\nEmpty/whitespace paths are filtered out. Ignored patterns are applied.\n\n### Source 2: INITIAL attributions (line 1142-1164)\n\n```rust\nfor file in working_log.read_initial_attributions().files.keys() {\n    let normalized_path = normalize_to_posix(file);\n    if !is_path_in_repo(&normalized_path) { continue; }\n    if should_ignore_file_with_matcher(&normalized_path, ignore_matcher) { continue; }\n    if is_text_file(working_log, &normalized_path) {\n        files.insert(normalized_path);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nINITIAL attributions are stored in `.git/ai/working_logs/{sha}/INITIAL` (a JSON file). They represent the attribution state inherited when a new working log is created — e.g., files that had AI attribution from a previous commit. Each file key is validated:\n- Must be inside the repo working directory\n- Must not match ignore patterns  \n- Must be a text file (no null bytes)\n\n### Source 3: Previous checkpoint entries (line 1166-1195)\n\n```rust\nif let Ok(working_log_data) = working_log.read_all_checkpoints() {\n    for checkpoint in &working_log_data {\n        for entry in &checkpoint.entries {\n            let normalized_path = normalize_to_posix(&entry.file);\n            if !is_path_in_repo(&normalized_path) { continue; }\n            if should_ignore_file_with_matcher(&normalized_path, ignore_matcher) { continue; }\n            if !files.contains(&normalized_path) {\n                if is_text_file(working_log, &normalized_path) {\n                    files.insert(normalized_path);\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAll files mentioned in any prior checkpoint for this base commit are re-included. This ensures continuity — if a file was tracked before, it stays tracked even if the agent doesn't explicitly mention it again. Stored in `.git/ai/working_logs/{sha}/checkpoints.jsonl` (JSONL format, one checkpoint per line).\n\n### Source 4: Git status scan (line 1197-1210)\n\nThe accumulated `files` set from Sources 1-3 is passed as pathspecs to `get_status_of_files()` (line 1039), which runs `git status --porcelain=v2 -z`.\n\n**Critical branching logic:**\n\n```rust\nlet has_ai_checkpoints = working_log_data.iter().any(|checkpoint| {\n    checkpoint.kind == CheckpointKind::AiAgent || checkpoint.kind == CheckpointKind::AiTab\n});\n\nlet results_for_tracked_files = if is_pre_commit && !has_ai_checkpoints {\n    get_status_of_files(repo, working_log, files, true, ignore_matcher)?   // skip_untracked=true\n} else {\n    get_status_of_files(repo, working_log, files, false, ignore_matcher)?  // skip_untracked=false\n};\n```\n\n- **Pre-commit with NO prior AI checkpoints:** `skip_untracked=true` — only tracks previously-known files, not brand-new untracked files. This avoids capturing noise before any AI work has happened.\n- **All other cases:** `skip_untracked=false` — includes untracked files, capturing full working directory state.\n\n### Source 5: Dirty files (line 1217-1240)\n\n```rust\nif let Some(ref dirty_files) = working_log.dirty_files {\n    for file_path in dirty_files.keys() {\n        let normalized_path = normalize_to_posix(file_path);\n        if !is_path_in_repo(&normalized_path) { continue; }\n        if should_ignore_file_with_matcher(&normalized_path, ignore_matcher) { continue; }\n        if !results_for_tracked_files.contains(&normalized_path) {\n            if is_text_file(working_log, &normalized_path) {\n                results_for_tracked_files.push(normalized_path);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nDirty files are file contents provided directly by the agent (not read from disk). Any dirty file not already in the results is added, ensuring agent-provided snapshots are always captured.\n\n### Final step: Preserve explicit pre-commit paths (line 1242-1259)\n\n```rust\nif preserve_explicit_pre_commit_paths {\n    for normalized_path in explicit_pre_commit_paths {\n        if !is_path_in_repo(&normalized_path) { continue; }\n        if should_ignore_file_with_matcher(&normalized_path, ignore_matcher) { continue; }\n        if results_for_tracked_files.contains(&normalized_path) { continue; }\n        if is_text_file(working_log, &normalized_path)\n            || is_text_file_in_head(repo, &normalized_path)\n        {\n            results_for_tracked_files.push(normalized_path);\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWhen `preserve_explicit_pre_commit_paths` is true (set when `i